{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958050901/0264.xml":{"full_text":"\u2018Most Prosperous Recession\u2019\nCheered at C of C Meeting\n'Labor was blamed for everything but the latest satellite\nsnafu at the 46th annual meeting of the Chamber of Com\nmerce of the U.S.A.\nMost of the 4,000 delegates to the sessions in Washing\nton cheered the claim than \u201cthis is the most prosperous re\ncession in U.S. history.\u2019\nI\nThe chamber members\nfrom around the country also'\ngave advance endorsement to the\nnomination of Vice Pres. Richard!\nM. Nixon as Republican standard'\nbearer in the 1960 presidential'\nrace.\nExhorted by Goldwater\nSen. Barry M. Goldwater (R.\nArii.), an arch-foe of unions,\nexhorted the delegates to greater\npolitical action this year and\nhenceforward if they wished to!\navoid dire consequences.\nI\n\u201cYou have been silent too'\nlong,\u201d Goldwater advised.\nGoldwater had some hard\nwords for his fellow senators\nwho failed to apply the hob\nbles to unions that he proposed\nin recent debate. He had some\nire left over for the lack of\nrapport he and fellow conserv\natives received from business\nmen.\nHe indicated, however, that he\nmeant businessmen generally\nand not the chamber, which he\nsaid was doing a good job. v\nMerger\n(Continued from Page 1)\ncould \"go off any minute\u201d dur\ning a recession, such\npresent.\nat\nas\nMr. Reuther told the dele\ngates:\n\u201cOnly through a voluntary\nagreement such as this can you\nbuild the basis for understand\ning. Unity will have no value\nunless you put it into practice in\nthe plant and in the neighbor\nhood.\u201d\n\"Unionism,\" he added, \"is not\na slot machine, in which you put\nyour dues and try to hit the\njackpot. Rather it is a set of\ntools with which workers\nbuild a better tomorrow.\"\ncan\nTony\u2019s Gulf Service\nDETROIT at LAWRENCE CH. 1-0069\nClem\u2019s Marathon Service\nDETROIT at PHILLIPS\nGR. 2-0342\nMiller\u2019s Pure Oil Service\nBERDAN at HAVERHILL\nGR. 5-7581\nw\nHerb\u2019s Gulf Service\nCOLLINGWOOD at ASHLAND\nI\nCH. 1-0432\nTOLEDO UNION\nJOURNAL\nTrading Post\nRates: 40 renli\na line (5 worth), minimum 2 Unci. 80\ncenti. Mail with caih or bring in to Room 203, 245 Rin\nthrop Street, CH. 1-9126, Hxtemion 33.\nFuneral Directors\nDAY-EDWARDS MORTUARY\n741 W. Central Ave\nCH 4-0751\nHOEFLINGER MORTUARY\nan putt at\nox. 1-6768\nFOTH MORTUARY\n2310 Jefferson Ave.\nCH 1-3241\nABELE FUNERAL HOME\n1010 Cherry St.\nCH 3-8161\nPARKS D. EMMERT FUNERAL HOME\nMil aa. ee\n3883 Monroe St.\nOR. 2-21 IS\nH. H. BIRKENKAMP FUNERAL\nHOMIS\u2014100S Broadway CH. 3-2183\nTRILBY. Ohio. GR 4-3772\nBROWN FUNERAL HOME\nHand Ava. CH. 2-8423\n818 Grand Ava.\nTelevision Sets\nTV SET. Home appliances all types.\n1854 W. Central Ava.\nHardware Supplies\nPAINTS all kinds, low prices. Colon\nial Hardware. 1884 Central.\nUsed Cars\nFOR SALE: Jeep Station Wagons\n4-wheel drive. CaU CH. 3-0071.\nTheodore R. Iserman, a New\nYork lawyer, delighted delegates\nwith a broadside against \"the\ngrowing power of unions.\"\nUnions and their leaders,\nIserman told the chamber,\n\u201ctoday constitute a more im\nmediate threat to our way of\nlife than does the military\nmight of Soviet Russia, with\nher sputniks, ballistic missiles\nand nuclear weapons.\u201d\nLabor leaders, Iserman con\ntinued, have in effect repealed\nthe law of supply and demand.\nI \u201cNotwithstanding layoffs, short\nworkweeks, growing unemploy\nment and relatively hard times\nin most areas of our economy.\nI unions, by forcing wages up.\nhave forced prices up for the\nfirst time in a recession.\"\nIserman added his voice in\nurging more political action and\neducation by members of cham\nbers, the National Association of\nManufacturers and trade associ\nations. Otherwise, he forecast\nunion officials and AFL-CIO\nCOPE might elect \u201ca subservient\nCongress.\u201d\nThe. chamber published a\nspecial booklet attacking the\nprofit sharing plan advanced\nby Auto Workers Pres. Walter\nP. Reuther. Lobby displays at\nthe convention Inveighed\nagainst \u201cunion abuses\u201d 'and\ncalled for \"right-to-work\u201d leg\nislation.\nSen. Karl E. Mundi (R S. D.)\nwas the speaker who called this\n\u201cthe most prosperous recession\nin U. S. history.\u201d He was cheered\nfrequently for his claim that\nstrikes and work stoppages are\nfewer than ever and that scan\ndal and corruption have disap\npeared from high places In gov\nernment.\nNixon Nomination Forecast\nThe loudest cheers came when\nhe predicted Nixon\u2019s nomination\nService\nGERBER CABINET SHOP\u2014Specialist\nin kitchen remodeling. CH 2-9337.\nPAY water, gas. phone. light bills at\nLocal 13 duos window.\nMall your Sales Tax Stamps to F\nReno. 433 Winthrop St.\nNEW YORK Lie Insurance Co. Rich\nerd C. Duffey Agent. CH. 8-6481.\nHall For Rent\u2014Kitehen facilities, 3015\nDetroit near Central CH 6-4806.\nCOTTON SHAG RUGS washed. dried,\ndyed re-rubberized 3-Hour service\non most rugs. Friendly Laundrymat.\n3644 Upton Ave. GR 4-6086.\nGive-lbAway\n1\nLooking for a good home for two\ndogs. a Terrier and a Boxer. JO. 7325\n1 tS MA. 1404 \u2022ta\nif no answer inquire at 1424 Detroit\nAve.\nMiscellaneoug\nFOR SALE: McGuffeys\nEelectie\nSpeller. Call Grand Rapids 21137\nWILL TRADE 3150 automatic washer\n(for small boat and motor. LU. 4-6930\nIt iktri tomething you no longer need and would like\nto give away to help tome other union member? Jutt call\nour \u201cGive Away Column,,> C Harry 1-9126, Ext. 33.\nfor the presidency two years\nhence.\nThe only Democratic office\nholder on the program, Sen.\nHubert H. Humphrey (Minn.)\nsaid: \u201cFellow Americans,\nwhat\u2019s going to happen to the\nRepublican Party in 1958\nshouldn't happen to a fellow\nAmerican.\u201d\nThe chamber saw itself in the\nrole of defender of \u201cthe worker\nand his family\u201d with a policy\ndeclaration considered at one of\nthe final sessions. It urged \u201cim\nmediate and effective action\u201d\nthrough \"right-to-work\" laws on\nthe federal and state levels.\nIn other areas of the labor\nmanagement field the chamber\ntook up policy statements urging\nthe repeal of minimum wage\nprovisions of the Walsh-Healey\nAct and limiting coverage un\nder\nthe\nFair\nLabor\nStandards\nAct and continuing exemption\nof workers in retail or service\nbusinesses.\nThe temporary existence of\nunusually high unemployment\nshould not be used as an argu\nment for a shorter workweek,\nanother policy declaration set\nforth.\nThe chamber came out against\nsympathy strikes, strikes in vio\nlation of contract, jurisdictional\nstrikes and strikes alleged to cor\nrect unfair labor practices.\nCut In Taxes\nTo Be Asked\nSen. Paul Douglas (D-Ill.)\nwill again introduce his bill\nto cut federal taxes, he an\nnounced on the AFL-CIO\npublic service radio program,\nWashington Reports to the Peo\nple.\nDouglas said he will increase\nthe proposed total reduction\nfrom $5 billion to $6 billion.\n\"We've allowed a lot of time\nto slip through our hands and\nthings are getting worse rather\nthan better,\" Douglas asserted.\n\"The longer we postpone action,\nthe more heroic remedies we\nwill have to adopt.\u201d\nAnswering the assertion that a\n[lax cut would not be of much\nassistance to the jobless, Doug\nlas said, \"the unemployed should\nbe primarily helped by extension\nand liberalizing of unemploy\nment insurance benefits.\n\"A tax cut would indirectly\naid\nthe unemployed singe it\nwould release purchasing pow\ner, enable people to buy more,\nthus causing industry to produce\nmore and hire more workers.\ni\n\"What this country needs most,\nis to restore production and em\nployment.\"\nMethodist Board\nHits -Wreck\u2019 Laws\nThe \"real menace\" of state\nlaws banning union shop agree\nments is that they deny \u201cby law\nthe possibility of increasing in\ndividual freedom,\u201d the National\nBoard of Social and Economic\nRelations of the Methodist\nChurch declared.\nThe board adopted a resolu\ntion asserting that such meas\n\u201cmiscalled \u2018right-to\nures\nare\nwork' laws since they do not ob\nligate anyone to give an indi\nvidual a job.\n\u201cWe hold that union member\nship as a basis of continued em\nployment should be left to agree\nment by management and labor\nthrough the process of collec\ni tive bargaining,\u201d\nboard said.\nthe church\nfzl\nt\n1\nMW\ni\nI\nmm cis\namoL\nX\nv-\nBacks Adoption of Merger\nJohn S. Johns, Steelworkers director at Canton, was\namong CIO leaders who urged merger. (Other merger\nphotos, Pages 1 and 2).\n\u2014Union Journal Photo\nHouse Hears Pleas\nFor Action on Slump\nWASHINGTON\u2014Enactment of a broad legislative pro\ngram to end the economic tailspin is long overdue, Auto\nWorkers Pres. Walter P. Reuther and Steelworkers Pres.\nDavid J. McDonald declared in testimony before the House\nBanking Committee.\nThe two union leaders\nblamed the recession in part\non the \"administered-pricing\"\npolicies of giant corporations,\nwhich pushed prices upward in\nthe face of declining demand.\nMcDonald and Reuther called\nfor prompt action on measures\nto raise and extend unemploy\nment compensation, lower taxes\nfor low and middle-income fam\nilies.\nextend\nminimum\nwage\ncoverage, and advance compre\nhensive public works programs.\nReuther told the House com\nmittee headed by Chairman\nBrent Spence (D-Ky), that if the\neconomic decline continues un\nchecked, the nation will suffer\na loss of $55 billion in its gross\nnational product.\nCause for Concern\nHe warned that the 78,000\ndrop in unemployment for mid\nApril was \u201ccause for concern\nand not cause for optimism,\u201d\nsince there normally is a sea\nsonal drop of 200,000 in jobless\nrolls from mid-March to mid\nApril.\nMcDonald lashed out at the\nEisenhower Administration for\n\u201cblindness and callousness\u201d in\nits reluctance to halt the re\ncession, adding that this put\nit \u201csquarely up to the Con\ngress to provide leadership\u201d\nin returning the country to\nfull production.\nThe two union presidents gave\nconsiderable emphasis in their\ntestimony to the. need for area\nredevelopment the issue for\nwhich the hearings originally\nwere planned.\nCites National Need\nReuther urged Congress to\nI \u201cend the industrial blight that\nhas been mushrooming through\nout America.\u201d He declared that\n.\u2018\u2018rede velopment of distressed\nareas is not a sectional need, it\nis a national need,\u201d and added:\n\u201cThe number of urban and\nrural areas in need of econom.\nic help is so great, the loss in\nmanpower and blighted lives\nas well as in dollars and cents\nis so enormous, that the prob\nlem demands national atten\ntion.\"\nLocal 16 To Show\n-Slave\u2019 Bill Skit\nAll union members in the To\nledo area are invited to a special\nmeeting of Local 16 UAW to\nmorrow, Saturday, May 10, to\nsee a skit, written and acted by\nworkers, on the \"Right to Slave\u201d\nbill.\nThe meeting will be at 8 p.m.\nin Local 16 Hall, 3016 Detroit\nAve. near West Central Ave. The\nhall accommodates 700 persons.\nThe skit will be presented by\nmembers of Local 128 UAW,\nTroy, O. to show how this type\nof legislation would wreck or\nganized labor in Ohio, said Doro\nthy Hubbell, president of Local\n16, which covers workers at\nDura Division of Detroit Har\nvester, and Prestole Corp.\nSpicer Man Attends\nCredit Union Talks\nJohn V. Nation, 4601 Willys\nParkway, treasurer of Spicer\nFederal Credit Union, represent\ned Ohio at international credit\nunion meetings May 5-11 in\nMadison, Wis.\nNation is a director of the\nCredit Union National Associa\ntion (CUNA). He was elected by\nOhio credit union members in\n1949 and has held this post since.\nCUNA is an international, non\nprofit organization serving 24,\n700 credit unions in the Western\nHemisphere with 12 million\n.members.\nNation has been active in cred\njit union work since 1936 and is\na past president of the Ohio\n(Credit\nUnion\nLeague, a\nstate\nwide association of credit unions.\nI\nWhere In The World Can You Beat It?\n9\n(44,\nFOR ECONOMY\n(29 Miles Per Gal.)\nPRICE SIZE\nV\nt\nit\nScotsman\u2019\n2\u2022Door Sedan\nAmerican-Made\nBy UAW-AFL-CIO\nUnion Workers\nONLY\nIncludes:\n$1795\nHeater, Defroster, Turning Signals,\nTubeless Tires, Rear-View Mirror,\nWindshield Wipers, Key Starter,\nAir Cleaner\u2014Incl. All Fed. Taxes\nDOWNTOWN\nSTUDEBAKER-PACKARD\nSALES, INC.\nJEFFERSON ONTARIO\nCH. 1-3151\n\nI\nU. S. Economy Autos Better Buys\n4\nThan Cramped Foreign Makes\nBy SIDNEY MARGOLIUS\nConsumer Buying Expert\nWhile the 1958 standard-size U.S. cars are far behind\nthis year, there\u2019s been a big increase in sales both of im\nported small cars and of the U.S. economy models, the\nRamblers and Studebaker Scotsman,\nDozens of imported makes are pouring into the U.S.\nfrom all over the world to ex\nploit this interest. Even G.M.\nand Ford are bringing in the\nsmall cars they make in other\ncountries, and are reported to be\nexploring production of small\ncars here.\nWhat are the facts about the\nimported cars?\n1\nJ&L\nWare\nBy TED MODROWSKI\nThe members of the J&L ex\ntend their deepest sympathy to\nMary Bishop in the loss of her\nsister, and to Leonard and Wal\nter Lykowski in the loss of\ntheir brother.\nMany thanks to Edna Retz\nloff for the very fine contribu\ntion of-tax stamps for the Local\n12 Summer Camp. We are now\nreaching that time of year when\nthe youngsters start dreaming\nof the wonderful times they\nwill have at the camp and we\ncan do a great deal to help them\nwith their dreams if we con\ntinue to pour in tax stamps.\nAny and all will be greatly ap\npreciated.\nBill Klaperek goes \u201call out\u201d\nfor these bowling \u2018Fun Night\u2019\ndeals which are proving to be\nso popular among the bowlers.\nBill became all enthused about\nan event of this nature which\nhe attended' last week and, fol\nlowing the night, he came in to\nwork with sox that were any\nthing but mates.\nWhen questioned regarding\nthe difference, his quick reply\nwas, \u201cI\u2019m- still having fun at the\n\u2019Fun Night\u2019 and I don\u2019t feel like\nstopping yet!\u201d\nWe are deeply disappointed\nin Blanche Strickler. It seems\nshe should have completed her\ndriving lessons and qualified for\nher driver\u2019s\nlicense by this\ntime but we haven\u2019t seen her\nname listed among the drivers\nat the local race track. How\ncome. Blanche?\nIf Ben Maciejewski hasn\u2019t\ntold you yet, have him tell you\nthe new story about Ike. It\u2019s\nsure a laugh-getter.\nGeorge Hackney and Jim\nWilliams journeyed to Buffalo\nto bowl in the National YMCA\nTournament and finished\nin\nfirst place winning a beautiful\ntrophy.\nGeorge opened his series with\na 225 to finish with a 558 and\nJim trailed with a 540 total.\nTheir 5-man team total which\nwas good for top honors was\n2970.\nThis same team, of which both\nGeorge and Jim are regular\nmembers, also took top honors\nin the Western Division of the\nYMCA Traveling League.\nCongratulations, men,\ngood job well done!\non a\nIt was very amusing to say\nthe least to read that Gov.\nO\u2019Neill said he needed no par\nticular speech to deliver in his\nbid for re-election to the office\nof Governor of Ohio. He said he\nwould \u201cstand on his record.\u201d\nIf he is a magician, which he\nwill have to be. he will be able\nto suspend himself in mid-air.\nHe did nothing in the past two\nyears, but a few political favors,\nso he has nothing to stand on.\nIf he is a magician like he is\na Governor, he is going to fall\nrather flat in trying to stand on\nthe \u2018do-nothing record\nActually they are not cheap\nto buy, but are only slightly\nmore economical to operate. The\nfour-cylinder imports run from\n$1500 to $2000 plus transporta\ntion from port of entry and some\nare as much and even more than\nstandard-transmission American\nsixes.\nThe recent! y-introduced\nRambler American, a six, lists\nat about $1790, the Scotsman\nat $1776 (including heater),\nand the other popular price\nAmerican sixes at $2050 to\n$2150 (F.O.B.).\nToo, while discounts are wide\nly available on the domestic\nmakes, the imported-car dealers\nhold their prices firmly.\nThe truth is, some of the for\ne ig n manufacturers, including\nthose whose homes are in the\nU.S., are not bringing in the real\neconomy models they sell\nabroad, but the de luxe models.\nAlso, supply seems closely\nenough gauged to the demand for\nthese cars so that there is no\npressure to trim prices.\nThe only saving is in gas. Most\nof these small four-cylinder im\nports average 32 miles on a gal\nlon. compared to the approxi\nmately 16, on the average, of an\nAmerican six, and the 14-15 for\neights. The economy-type Ameri\ncan cars, such as Rambler and\nScotsman, are producing about\n18-24 miles per gallon, owners\nreport.\nYou can estimate a standard\nsize popular-price American six\nwill average about 2 cents a mile\nfor fuel, the compact-type Amer-,\nican sixes, about 1.3 to 1.7 cents,\nand the small imports, about 1\ncent. Since American gasoline\nprices are about half of Europe's,\nthe savings per mile is not nearly\nas important here.\nA family that does a mod\n$7.17\nPER MONTH\nPER $1,000 BORROWED\nPAYS THE\nPRINCIPAL and INTEREST\nON A HOME\nOF YOUR OWN\nThe HOME\nBUILDING SAVINGS CO\n902 Broadway\n2202 W CENTRAL AVt\n2670 WOODVILLE RD\nerate 6000-7000 miles a year,\nmay not find the fuel savings\nas vital since small imports\nalso have at least one financial\ndisadvantage. Reports indicate\nthat some of the foreign car\nrepair specialists are charging\nstiff prices, and replacement\nparts also are sometimes cost\nly.\nin driving, the only advant@e\nof the small cars is easy hand*\nling in traffic and parking. For\none thing, they have less over*\nhang than the American\ncars.\nThe actual wheelbases are not\nas much smaller as the overall\nsize.\nOn long trips, the ride pro\nvided by the small cars is stiffer,\nand the quarters may seem\ncramped to a large family. The\nlower power becomes most not\niceable on hills, where extra\ngear-shifting is required. In gen\neral, these cars seem more suit\nable for city driving than over\nthe-road.\nThe solution for moderate\nincome families who need one\ncar for all driving purposes at\na reasonable price, still is not\na small car at close to 02000,\nnor a power-packed mam\nmoth. It is more likely to 66\none of the more compact\nstandard shift sixes.\nSEWER CLOGGED? Cl Your\nROTO-ROOTER\nService Man\nCH 4-4871\nFree Estimates\nAll Sewer Jobs\nGuaranteed 2 Years\n23 Years Satisfied Service\n1713 DETROIT AVENUE\nGIVE\nYOURSELF\nA GOOD\nBRAKE\nW\nly The\nExperts\nTURNER\nBRAKE SERVICE\nlll-14th St. CH. 3-8255\nBring This Ad for $5\nOff AH Repairs Over $50\nJACK GRIMES\nAutomotive Service, Inc.\n946 Eleanor at Lewie\n\nAUTOMATIC\nTRANSMISSION\nSPECIALISTS\nA Good Service for Auto Workers\u2014\n(WAY-)) TOLEDO AUTO CLUB\n2271 Ashland Avenue\nCH. 1-4142\nUNDERCOATING\nALL\nCARS\nComplete Undercoating, Including Rood,\nFenders, Gm Tank and Underbody\nWe use the finest undercoating material\navailable. Guaranteed. Steam cleaning\nTOLEDO UNDERCOATING CO.\nOpen 8-6 Monday Through Saturday\n4545 Monroe St. (Near Secor Rd.) New Exchange GR. 5-1811\nI\nBUY AMERICAN-BUY RAMBLER\nIt's America's Answer to the Foreign Car Challenge\u2014\nFor American Big-Car' Family Room and Comfort\nW ith European Small-Car Economy and Handling Ease\nGo Rambler! 35 Miles Per Gallon W/ith Overdrive\nRambler Prices Start $1921. Includes Weather-Eye, Heater,\u2019\nTurn Signals, Tubeless Tires, 12-Volt System, Unitized Body\nImmediate\nDelivery\n9\n00\nMade By\nUAW-AFL-CIO\nUnion Members\n$.3\ngh\nREGAL RAMBLER\n\nWHERE EVERY CUSTOMER IS TREATED AS ROYALTY\n1122 MONROE at 12th\n\nCH 3-9235","height":"26892","width":"19592"}}
